<paragraph id="8BD436C2873DAA2246A0FA70DAECACCA" blockId="38.[189,1399,1410,1775]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
This species was described based on a single female specimen collected in Cacao, northern 
<collectingCountry id="F37C7652873DAA2242D3FA70DE30AFB9" box="[1230,1360,1410,1436]" name="Guatemala" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, by two renowned entomologists, the German-American Eugene Amandus Schwarz (
<date id="FFD51002873DAA22426AFA5EDF9FAFE3" box="[1143,1279,1452,1478]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" value="1844" valueMax="1928">1844–1928</date>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFA4B33873DAA22430BFA5EDB99AFD4" author="Howard" firstAuthor="Howard" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="154 - 183" refId="ref20992" refString="Howard L. O. 1928. Dr. E. A. Schwarz. Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington 30 (9): 154 - 183." type="journal article" year="1928">Howard 1928</bibRefCitation>
) and the American Herbert Spencer Barber (
<date id="FFD51002873DAA22451FFA24D8EDAFD4" box="[770,909,1494,1521]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" value="1882" valueMax="1950">1882–1950</date>
). Both researchers were skillful collectors specialized in the study of beetles (
<bibRefCitation id="EFFA4B33873DAA224448F9F3D998AC3E" author="Caudell" box="[597,760,1537,1563]" firstAuthor="Caudell" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="169 - 176" refId="ref19300" refString="Caudell A. N. 1907. On some earwigs (Forficulidae) collected in Guatemala by messrs. Schwarz and Barber. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 33 (1563): 169 - 176." type="journal article" year="1907">Caudell 1907</bibRefCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="54D08860873DAA22455DF9F3D8C7AC3E" box="[832,935,1537,1563]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation id="13502A47873DAA2245ABF9F3DF6CAC3E" box="[950,1036,1537,1563]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="39.[189,232,768,794]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,728]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[189,1398,265,728]" captionText="Fig. 28. Centris schwarzi Cockerell, 1919, holotype, ♀ (NMNH; USNM ENT 00534214). A. Frontal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bars: A = 1 mm; B = 2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3723004" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3723004/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
) is currently housed at 
<collectionCode id="ED7AAE07873DAA224300F9F3DE17AC3E" box="[1309,1399,1537,1563]" country="USA" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/142r-0w94" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="Museum">NMNH</collectionCode>
and has the following data label: Cacao [printed] 1904 26.3 [handwritten] Guat [printed]\ Alta V. Paz 
<collectingCountry id="F37C7652873DAA2246A0F9A7DA5CAC4A" box="[189,316,1621,1647]" name="Guatemala" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
[printed]\ Barber &amp; Schwarz Coll [printed]\ 
<taxonomicName id="4C6B4D41873DAA22457AF9A4DF16AC55" authority="Ckll." authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1919" box="[871,1142,1621,1648]" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schwarzi">
<emphasis id="B91FEAD0873DAA22457AF9A4DF51AC4A" box="[871,1073,1621,1648]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Centris schwarzi</emphasis>
Ckll.
</taxonomicName>
Type. [handwritten]\ [red label] Type No. [printed] 21657 [handwritten] 
<collectingCountry id="F37C7652873DAA22452EF972D805ACBF" box="[819,869,1664,1690]" name="United States of America" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">U.S.</collectingCountry>
N.M. [printed]\ [yellow label] USNM ENT 00534214 [barcode] [printed]\\ DO NOT REMOVE SI DB Reference Not a property tag T. Schultz 
